JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 91
IS  - 2
SP  - 720
EP  - 747
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - Uncertainty rises in recessions and falls in booms. But what is the causal relationship? We construct cross-country panel data on stock market returns to proxy for first- and second-moment shocks and instrument these with natural disasters, terrorist attacks, and political shocks. Our IV regression results reveal a robust negative short-term impact of second moments (uncertainty) on growth. Employing multiple vector autoregression estimation approaches, relying on a range of identifying assumptions, also reveals a negative impact of uncertainty on growth. Finally, we show that these results are reproducible in a conventional micro–macro business cycle model with time-varying uncertainty.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdad036
